satisfiable rules. This also only rebuilds changed parts, whereas the
old rule recreated all firmware dependencies unconditionally.

Also split linker LINKFLAGS from compile SDCCFLAGS.

Merge pull request #21 from StefanBruens/master

Cleanup of autovector interrupt code

Avoid multiple evaluation of argument to RESETTOGGLE macro

If the argument evaluation has side effects, the expansion has unwanted
effects. Also the evaluation may be expensive (e.g. fetching data from
a volatile register).
The new code can be better optimized by sdcc, and avoids fetching contents
from the volatile TOGCTL register.

replace USB/GPIF autovector asm code with normal interrupt

The jump table is target for both the USB as the GPIF interrupt. Including
autovector.h references the _gpif_isr/_usb_isr symbols and forces linking
of the jump table.

Signed-off-by: Stefan Brüns <stefan.bruens@rwth-aachen.de>

cleanup interrupt code

Autovector interrupts should not specify an interrupt number, as these
creates unnecessary entries in the interrupt table, wasting 8 bytes
of direct adressable memory per entry.
The entry for interrupt 13 (which is nonexistant) is used to reserve
enough space for the overlays for interrupt 8 (USB) and 10 (GPIF).

Signed-off-by: Stefan Brüns <stefan.bruens@rwth-aachen.de>

Merge pull request #11 from sylphase/bugfixes

Bugfixes

eputils: NAKALL must be kept asserted until last fifo is reset.

As specified in
  EZ-USB® Technical Reference Manual, Document # 001-13670 Rev. *D
(and since rev. *A), table C-1 page 384:
  Set flags and byte counts to default
  values; write 0x80 to NAK all trans-
  fers, then write NAKALL OR’ed with
  FIFO number, then write 0x00 to re-
  store normal operation
Use most conservative SYNCDELAY in gpif.c, since it's precompiled and we don't know what speeds will be used.
Added all the possibly useful SYNCDELAYs so that SYNCDELAY can be defined with sdcc's -D option, e.g. in a Makefile.

Separate int4 interrupts from int2 interrupts.

The addition of another assembly file for the int4 auto vector overlay
allows usage of usb interrupts without also using gpif interrupts.  This
allows the gpif interrupt to be used with an external interrupt handler
instead of the gpif autovector (enable the INT4 pin for instance.)

Optional LIBS argument in Makefile.

Allows more easily linking with additional libraries besides the fx2.lib.

Ability of fx2 driver example to open by index.

Changed open method to have an optional index parameter.  This allows
opening more than one device at a time.  Also removed asserts so python
mappings don't seg fault.

Update framework Makefile to use fx2.mk

Add ability to override CC flags more easily.

Allows specifically descriptor area and int2jt areas to be
blanked out so simple firmwares for test devices can compile without
warning.  Also allows a firmware to more easily customize amount
of code and xram data space.

Updated i2c eeprom documentation.

clean-all target

clean now only cleans the project directory. clean-all cleans the fx2 library
in addition.  This allows the firmware to be cleaned and rebuilt without having
to rebuild fx2lib every time.

Clarify comments in azure-ci.yml (#400)

These rows in conjunction got me confused for a while:

      # To record on Cypress dashboard we need to set CYPRESS_RECORD_KEY environment variable
      # environment variable BUILD_BUILDNUMBER is a good candidate

As an unexperienced Cypress user, I assumed the RECORD_KEY was supposed to be my BUILDNUMBER.

This is clearly not the case, since the following error will be produced:
> Errors: [ "data.recordKey must be uuid format" ]

My change should suffice to clarify that doubt, but I'm sure you as domain experts can improve it as well.

Merge pull request #21 from StefanBruens/master

Cleanup of autovector interrupt code

Avoid multiple evaluation of argument to RESETTOGGLE macro

If the argument evaluation has side effects, the expansion has unwanted
effects. Also the evaluation may be expensive (e.g. fetching data from
a volatile register).
The new code can be better optimized by sdcc, and avoids fetching contents
from the volatile TOGCTL register.

replace USB/GPIF autovector asm code with normal interrupt

The jump table is target for both the USB as the GPIF interrupt. Including
autovector.h references the _gpif_isr/_usb_isr symbols and forces linking
of the jump table.

Signed-off-by: Stefan Brüns <stefan.bruens@rwth-aachen.de>

cleanup interrupt code

Autovector interrupts should not specify an interrupt number, as these
creates unnecessary entries in the interrupt table, wasting 8 bytes
of direct adressable memory per entry.
The entry for interrupt 13 (which is nonexistant) is used to reserve
enough space for the overlays for interrupt 8 (USB) and 10 (GPIF).

Signed-off-by: Stefan Brüns <stefan.bruens@rwth-aachen.de>

Merge pull request #11 from sylphase/bugfixes

Bugfixes

eputils: NAKALL must be kept asserted until last fifo is reset.

As specified in
  EZ-USB® Technical Reference Manual, Document # 001-13670 Rev. *D
(and since rev. *A), table C-1 page 384:
  Set flags and byte counts to default
  values; write 0x80 to NAK all trans-
  fers, then write NAKALL OR’ed with
  FIFO number, then write 0x00 to re-
  store normal operation
Use most conservative SYNCDELAY in gpif.c, since it's precompiled and we don't know what speeds will be used.
Added all the possibly useful SYNCDELAYs so that SYNCDELAY can be defined with sdcc's -D option, e.g. in a Makefile.

Changelog and Readme
Clean target to remove interrupt artifacts.
Update examples for use with new default interrupt handlers.
framework no longer needs default interrupts in firmware code.
Add default interrupt handlers for usb and gpif interrupts.
Update firmware framework to reflect changed headers

Separate int4 interrupts from int2 interrupts.

The addition of another assembly file for the int4 auto vector overlay
allows usage of usb interrupts without also using gpif interrupts.  This
allows the gpif interrupt to be used with an external interrupt handler
instead of the gpif autovector (enable the INT4 pin for instance.)

Optional LIBS argument in Makefile.

Allows more easily linking with additional libraries besides the fx2.lib.

Ability of fx2 driver example to open by index.

Changed open method to have an optional index parameter.  This allows
opening more than one device at a time.  Also removed asserts so python
mappings don't seg fault.
Correct Bulk loop product Id in Makefile.
Update framework Makefile to use fx2.mk

Add ability to override CC flags more easily.

Allows specifically descriptor area and int2jt areas to be
blanked out so simple firmwares for test devices can compile without
warning.  Also allows a firmware to more easily customize amount
of code and xram data space.

Moved fx2.mk to lib directory.
Updated i2c eeprom documentation.

clean-all target

clean now only cleans the project directory. clean-all cleans the fx2 library
in addition.  This allows the firmware to be cleaned and rebuilt without having
to rebuild fx2lib every time.

Modified the eeprom read/write routines to return FALSE if the i2c
read/write commands didn't work.
Also modified i2c_write to try again (similar to first implementation)
if no ACK received after writing the address.  I found the eeprom on the
development board sometimes does not ack the first time.  TRM says to
try again in this case.  A side effect of this is you need to make sure
you are writing to an address that exists or the command will block.

Adding solution file for the AirQualityMX repo

Solution file for dotnet project is currently listing 3(will grow) main projects
located in the following directories.
- airquality/src: Will hold projects which convert to class libraries
and will have code to be executed in production as part of the "system"
- airquality/tst: holds code that will "test" the "system"
- airqualityCdk: holds code that will represent the cloud infastructure,
such as the "stacks" of the system. Used to automate deployment and
manage resources in the system.

Note: although "Cdk" is not required to build/test the code itself,
having it in the root sln file will let VSCode to properly apply C#
Intellisense

AirQuality src and tst structure first commit

AirQuality project will hold in this repo both, source code for class
library and also a tst directory which will use xunit for unit testing.
Integration tests are still out of scope but should(for the time being)
be put into the 'tst' directory.

Cloud infrastructure project first commit

In oderder to deploy this project into AWS cloud, we are using the AWS
CDK(Cloud development kit) which allows using code to define necessary
cloud resources. Initial commit considers one stack(assumed to be
development only) for initial deployment.

7.4.0 Release (#3928)

Co-authored-by: Chris Breiding <chrisbreiding@users.noreply.github.com>

Remove superfluous reference to .cache

Cypress by default caches its binaries to `~/.cache`, but since this can't be cached by GitLab CI the docs suggests to change the cache directory like this: `CYPRESS_CACHE_FOLDER: "$CI_PROJECT_DIR/cache/Cypress"`. It then tells you to cache the new cache directory: `- cache/Cypress`. This means that caching `.cache/*` is superfluous.

mocha-multi-reporters is broken for mocha 6+, which is what users will get if they run the suggested command:

```
npm install --save-dev mocha mocha-multi-reporters mocha-junit-reporter
```

Merge pull request #1062 from textbook/fix-clock-docs

Correct API documentation for clock command

Correct API documentation for clock command

The current documentation claims that the `now` parameter should be a `Date`, but the examples (and [the test suite](https://github.com/cypress-io/cypress/blob/b2e7148dbef87289336bdbaf39020d22a5544d1f/packages/driver/test/cypress/integration/commands/clock_spec.coffee#L30)) show that it actually expects the UNIX timestamp as a `number`. When we tried to use a `Date` object, we always ended up at the start of the UNIX epoch.

Please don't use implicit variable declarations!

This should be an error when running JavaScript in ES5 "strict mode," because implicit variables in JavaScript become globals. It's a small thing, but having the declaration (const/let/var, whichever -- although I've used `const` out of preference), will hopefully reduce confusion for beginners (who should expect all variables to be declared!) and make the code more idiomatic.

result in SIGBUS (bus error) on some architectures.

default libusb context without interference.
